messages.reasoning_content:
I found it! There's already some handling for this pattern at lines 4565-4577:

```cpp
// ((X ^ -1) ^ Y) s< (X ^ -1) --> (X ^ Y) s> X
// ((X ^ -1) ^ Y) s> (X ^ -1) --> (X ^ Y) s< X
// This uses the identity: (~A) cmp (~B) <=> A (flipped_cmp) B for signed comparisons
if (ICmpInst::isSigned(Pred) && !ICmpInst::isEquality(Pred)) {
  Value *Y;
  if (match(Op0, m_OneUse(m_c_Xor(m_Specific(Op1), m_Value(Y))))) {
    Value *X;
    if (match(Op1, m_OneUse(m_c_Xor(m_Value(X), m_AllOnes())))) {
      CmpInst::Predicate NewPred = ICmpInst::getSwappedPredicate(Pred);
      return new ICmpInst(NewPred, Builder.CreateXor(X, Y), X);
    }
  }
}
```

But let me trace through the test case:
- %3 = xor %0, -1  (so %3 = ~%0)
- %4 = xor %3, %1  (so %4 = %3 ^ %1)
- icmp slt %4, %3  means: (%3 ^ %1) <s %3

So we have:
- Op0 = %4 = xor %3, %1
- Op1 = %3 = xor %0, -1

The pattern at line 4570 matches:
```cpp
match(Op0, m_OneUse(m_c_Xor(m_Specific(Op1), m_Value(Y))))
```

This would match if Op0 is a one-use XOR of Op1 and some value Y. 

I need to verify whether Op0 actually has a single use in the IR. Looking at the test case, %4 is only used once in the comparison, so the one-use constraint should be satisfied. The pattern requires Op0 to be a one-use XOR of Op1 and another value Y, which matches our structure where %4 = xor %3, %1 and %3 is the other operand.

